{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "02 — Goroutines, Channels & Select",
  "description": "Go's signature feature: lightweight concurrency through goroutines and channels. This tour traces the real patterns in Balaur's embedded inference engine (internal/kronk): a mutex guarding resident native models, a lazy run-once initializer, the ChatStream entry point, a goroutine + buffered channel that bridges the model's token stream into the agent loop, a select that handles cancellation, and a teardown path that releases native memory.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/engine.go",
      "line": 36,
      "title": "2.1 — Engine: struct with a mutex",
      "description": "```go\ntype Engine struct {\n    mu        sync.Mutex\n    libPath   string\n    processor string\n    inited    bool\n\n    chatPath string\n    chat     *kronk.Kronk\n    embPath  string\n    emb      *kronk.Kronk\n}\n```\n\n`sync.Mutex` is Go's mutual-exclusion lock. The lowercase fields are unexported — nothing outside the `kronk` package can touch them directly.\n\nThe mutex is needed because the resident `*kronk.Kronk` models are mutable shared state: a web turn and a cron turn (recap, nudge, briefing) can both reach the engine concurrently. Loading or swapping a model mutates `chat`/`chatPath`; without the lock two goroutines could load at once — a data race the Go race detector would catch.\n\nThe canonical Go mutex pattern: **lock immediately, defer unlock immediately**, so you can never forget to unlock even if you add early returns later. Every method that touches `chat` or `emb` follows this pattern — see steps 2.3 and 2.6."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/engine.go",
      "line": 73,
      "title": "2.2 — ensureInit: run-once, the check-then-act guard",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (e *Engine) ensureInit() error {\n    if e.inited || kronk.Initialized() {\n        e.inited = true\n        return nil\n    }\n    libDir, err := resolveLibDir(e.libPath, e.processor)\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    if err := kronk.Init(kronk.WithLibPath(libDir)); err != nil {\n        return fmt.Errorf(\"initializing local inference runtime (%s): %w\", e.processor, err)\n    }\n    e.inited = true\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nThe Kronk SDK's `Init` may run **only once per process** — it `dlopen`s the llama.cpp native library, and a second call would panic. This is the idiomatic Go \"check-then-act\" guard: if the runtime is already initialized, return immediately; otherwise resolve the native library directory and initialize.\n\nThe caller always holds `e.mu` (see step 2.3), so the guard is safe against concurrent first-inference calls racing to initialize. Initialization is lazy — a box with no model and no native library still boots cleanly; the cost is paid on first real inference. AGENTS.md rule: *deterministic, offline, free behavior is the default; network and native paths are opt-in.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/engine.go",
      "line": 125,
      "title": "2.3 — chatModel: load/swap a resident model under the lock",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (e *Engine) chatModel(ctx context.Context, ggufPath string) (*kronk.Kronk, error) {\n    e.mu.Lock()\n    defer e.mu.Unlock()\n    if e.chat != nil && e.chatPath == ggufPath {\n        return e.chat, nil\n    }\n    if err := e.ensureInit(); err != nil {\n        return nil, err\n    }\n    if e.chat != nil {\n        _ = e.chat.Unload(ctx)\n        e.chat, e.chatPath = nil, \"\"\n    }\n    krn, err := kronk.New(...)\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n`Lock()` then `defer Unlock()` on the first two lines — the whole load/swap is serialized. If the resident model already matches the requested path, return it warm with no cost. Otherwise unload the old native model (freeing its memory) and load the new one.\n\nThis is reload-on-switch: one model stays resident, and changing the active model pays a full unload+load on the next turn. Holding `mu` for the duration means a concurrent turn waits rather than racing on `e.chat`. The same pattern is mirrored in `embedModel` for the embedding model."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/client.go",
      "line": 41,
      "title": "2.4 — ChatStream: the llm.Client entry point",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (c *Client) ChatStream(\n    ctx context.Context,\n    msgs []llm.Message,\n    tools []llm.ToolSpec,\n) (<-chan llm.Chunk, error) {\n    krn, err := c.eng.chatModel(ctx, c.chatPath)\n    ...\n    src, err := krn.ChatStreaming(ctx, d)\n    ...\n    return bridge(ctx, src, cancel), nil\n}\n```\n\n`ChatStream` implements the `llm.Client` interface seam — everything above `internal/turn` is provider-agnostic and only ever calls this method. The implementation here:\n\n1. Acquires the resident chat model (via the mutex in step 2.3)\n2. Ensures the context has a deadline — `chatStreamTimeout` (10 min) is added when the caller supplies none, because Kronk's streaming requires one\n3. Calls `krn.ChatStreaming` to start the native inference\n4. Bridges the result channel through the Go concurrency layer (step 2.5)\n\nThe returned `<-chan llm.Chunk` is a **receive-only channel** — the caller can read from it but cannot send. This is Go's way of expressing ownership: only `bridge`'s goroutine writes to it.\n\nTour 03 covers the other end of this channel — how the agent loop drains it with `for chunk := range stream`. From there the chat streaming writer in `internal/web/chat.go` adapts each event into a Datastar SSE patch (Tour 07)."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/client.go",
      "line": 97,
      "title": "2.5 — bridge: goroutine + buffered channel",
      "description": "```go\nfunc bridge(ctx context.Context, src <-chan model.ChatResponse,\n    cancel context.CancelFunc) <-chan llm.Chunk {\n    out := make(chan llm.Chunk, 8)\n    go func() {\n        defer close(out)\n        defer cancel()\n        ...\n    }()\n    return out\n}\n```\n\n`make(chan llm.Chunk, 8)` creates a **buffered channel** with capacity 8: up to 8 `Chunk` values can sit in the pipe before a send blocks. Without a buffer every send would block until the caller reads; a small buffer lets the goroutine run slightly ahead of the reader — useful when the model emits tokens faster than the gateway can render them.\n\n`bridge` returns `out` immediately — the goroutine keeps running in the background, translating Kronk's `model.ChatResponse` stream into Balaur's provider-neutral `llm.Chunk`s (content deltas, reasoning deltas, accumulated tool calls).\n\nTwo `defer` calls at the top of the goroutine:\n- `defer close(out)` — **when the goroutine exits for any reason**, the channel closes, so the consumer's `for chunk := range out` in Tour 03 cleanly ends. Without it the range loop would wait forever.\n- `defer cancel()` — releases the deadline context once the stream is fully drained, preventing a goroutine leak on the Kronk side."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/client.go",
      "line": 106,
      "title": "2.6 — select: cancellation on every send",
      "description": "```go\nsend := func(ch llm.Chunk) bool {\n    select {\n    case out <- ch:\n        return true\n    case <-ctx.Done():\n        return false\n    }\n}\n```\n\n`select` is Go's **switch for channels**: it waits until one case is ready, then runs exactly that one. Here it guards every send into `out`:\n\n- **Send case**: if the reader is keeping up, the chunk goes into the buffer and `send` returns true.\n- **Cancellation case**: if the context was cancelled — the owner navigated away, the request closed, a timeout hit — `ctx.Done()` is closed and `select` fires the second case. `send` returns false and the goroutine exits via `return`.\n\nWithout `select`, a cancelled context would leave the goroutine blocked on `out <-` forever when nobody is reading — a **goroutine leak** that persists until the process dies. This is the canonical Go cancellation idiom: guard a send with a `ctx.Done()` case so a gone consumer can never wedge the writer.\n\nThe `send` helper is defined as a function literal (closure) so the pattern is written once and reused for content chunks, reasoning chunks, error chunks, and the final done chunk."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/engine.go",
      "line": 179,
      "title": "2.7 — Close: teardown under the lock",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (e *Engine) Close(ctx context.Context) error {\n    e.mu.Lock()\n    defer e.mu.Unlock()\n    if e.chat != nil {\n        _ = e.chat.Unload(ctx)\n        e.chat, e.chatPath = nil, \"\"\n    }\n    if e.emb != nil {\n        _ = e.emb.Unload(ctx)\n        e.emb, e.embPath = nil, \"\"\n    }\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\n`Close` is the symmetric counterpart to `chatModel`/`embedModel`: it acquires the same mutex, unloads both resident native models, and clears the pointers. Called from the `OnTerminate` PocketBase hook in `main.go` alongside the FTS5 search-index teardown.\n\nUnloading the native models frees the memory the llama.cpp library allocated; without this the OS would reclaim it on process exit anyway, but explicit teardown is the right discipline for a resident-memory pattern.\n\nSetting `e.chat = nil` after unload means any goroutine that acquired `mu` before `Close` and is waiting will find `e.chat == nil` on the next `chatModel` call, triggering a clean reload error rather than a use-after-free. The `_ = e.chat.Unload(ctx)` discards the error by convention — teardown errors are not actionable at shutdown time."
    }
  ]
}
